frameDefinitions: An Agent acts so as to cause some process to begin again after an interruption or suspension.
A Member is semi-permanently part of a socially constructed Group.
The size of an Entity is assessed in terms of the Degree by which it deviates from the norm.
This frame is concerned with nouns denoting a part or parts of a Whole entity .
A Cognizer construes an Item as belonging to a certain Category.
A Producer produces a Product from a Resource for commercial purposes. '
frameExamples: The two countries <t>revived</t> diplomatic relations after a lull of five years.
Victor is <t>part</t> of the Red Crescent
Kim forgot a large <t><fex name='Part'>part</fex></t> of the story.
You 've already <t>stereotyped</t> me as a bimbo, have n't you?
They <t>produced</t> only half of the units after an injunction to follow the environmental policy.
listRoleDefinitions: A sentient being acts with the intention of causing a process to begin again.
The process which begins again after a suspension.
The period of time during which the process is suspended.
An animate or inanimate entity, a force, or event that causes the process to resume. Volitionality is not a necessary characteristic of Causes.
The time at which the process is restarted.
The location where the <fen>Agent</fen> causes the <fen>Process</fen> to resume.
The person who belongs to a <fen>Group</fen>.
A set of people standing in a semi-permanent relationship together.
The time at which the <fen>Member</fen> is a member of the <fen>Group</fen>.
The location where the membership relationship holds.
The thing whose size is being considered.
A <fen>Part</fen> of a larger <fen>Whole</fen>.
An undivided entity having all its <fen>Part</fen>s.
This is the person who performs an act of categorization. Typically, this frame element is expressed as an External Argument.
This is the entity which is construed or treated by the <fen>Cognizer</fen> as being an instance of a particular <fen>Category</fen>. Typically, the <fen>Item</fen> is expressed as an Object.

This frame element expresses a general type or class of which the <fen>Item</fen> is considered an instance. Typically, it is expressed in a prepositional phrase headed by <ment>as</ment> or <ment>under</ment>.

This frame element expresses properties of the <fen>Item</fen> which is used as a basis for categorization. <fen>Criteria</fen> are the general dimensions along which <fen>Item</fen>s can potentially differ from one another and hence, fall into different <fen>Category</fen>s. For example, a paint sample can be classified <ment>by color</ment> or <ment>by finish (matte or gloss)</ment>; if they are classified by color, one can be classified <ment>as orange</ment> and another <ment>as red</ment>. The <fen>Criteria</fen> role is typically expressed as a PP headed by <ment>by</ment>, or as a complex PP of the form <ment>on the basis of...</ment>:
This Frame Element marks expressions that indicate when a certain Categorization was made.
The person or company that produces the Product.
The <fen>Product</fen> is produced by the <fen>Producer</fen>.
<fen>Factory</fen> identifies the particular plant where the <fen>Product</fen> is manufactured.
This Fe identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the product was produced.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Product</fen> is manufactured.
